00:03:43.239 --> 00:03:47.110
The resolution is standard definition
but it's super slow motion,

00:03:47.110 --> 00:03:50.160
it's a really, really great option if you
want to capture

00:03:50.160 --> 00:03:53.709
and slow down fast action. Let's talk about

00:03:53.709 --> 00:03:57.270
aspect ratio next very briefly. The aspect ratio

00:03:57.270 --> 00:04:00.720
is the shape of your screen, okay,

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:05.160
and on the GoPro you can shoot in 17x9

00:04:05.160 --> 00:04:08.140
which is wide screen format, 16x9 which

00:04:08.150 --> 00:04:11.480
isn't quite as wide, or 4x3.

00:04:11.480 --> 00:04:15.700
Now the sensor on the GoPro is shaped 4x3,

00:04:15.700 --> 00:04:19.079
so when you shoot in 16x9 it will

00:04:19.079 --> 00:04:22.890
chop the top and bottom off the frame to
give you a wide framed picture,

00:04:22.890 --> 00:04:27.320
the same with 17x9. So let's look at the
difference between 16x9

00:04:27.320 --> 00:04:31.250
and 4x3 in these two clips,
when you play them side by side

00:04:31.250 --> 00:04:35.750
it's quite obvious, the clip on the
left is shot in ultra-wide 19x9,

00:04:35.750 --> 00:04:39.700
at 1080 resolution while the clip on the right is shot at 960

00:04:39.700 --> 00:04:44.160
within aspect ratio of 4x3. What's
interesting about the GoPro

00:04:44.160 --> 00:04:47.360
is that you could also shoot in super
view, now

00:04:47.360 --> 00:04:51.630
they say it's the most immersive video
picture available,

00:04:51.630 --> 00:04:58.110
and actually it is, the reason for this
is super view uses the entire 4x3 sensor

00:04:58.110 --> 00:05:01.760
and it stretches the sides, so you get the
full height,

00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:04.810
and the full width of the sensor but with extra width

00:05:04.810 --> 00:05:08.570
so it shoots at a 16x9 format, it looks
super wide

00:05:08.570 --> 00:05:11.670
it's got super great quality, it's really lovely.

00:05:11.670 --> 00:05:16.980
You can see this really clearly in this clip, see how charlie's arms are stretched each side of her,

00:05:16.980 --> 00:05:20.710
and we are able to see a lot more headroom, and a lot further down her body,

00:05:20.710 --> 00:05:23.050
you're getting a really wide angle of view.

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:29.760
Sometimes you aren't going to be its get close enough
to your subject, to be able to see everything

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:32.200
that's when you use your fields of view.

00:05:32.200 --> 00:05:35.760
Now on some resolutions you've got options,
you can shoot wide,

00:05:35.760 --> 00:05:39.190
you can shoot medium, and you can shoot
narrow fields of view.

00:05:39.190 --> 00:05:43.160
This is exactly the same as zooming in
or zooming out on a standard camera,

00:05:43.160 --> 00:05:47.670
or changing the lens. At 1080, you can
also choose a range of frame rates

00:05:47.670 --> 00:05:50.950
with really good quality thats useful for
a range of applications,

00:05:50.950 --> 00:05:54.910
add to that the benefit of being able to
change the field of view

00:05:54.910 --> 00:05:59.070
and actually it starts to be a really good
option for most productions

